{"source_key":"sha256-f6bbf31bf9e6709157d23bb2425b0d13","record_index":3119,"record_hash":"sha256:872bb9f053a3ec17cf6a3ec3e0cca5bda64120542761dda645c72a2378a49c23","timestamp":"2026-06-03T13:40:34.484Z","kind":"tool_result","source_event_kind":"codex:response_item:function_call_output","role":null,"text":"Chunk ID: 1a451f\nWall time: 0.6293 seconds\nProcess exited with code 0\nOriginal token count: 703\nOutput:\n{\"data\":{\"repository\":{\"pullRequest\":{\"reviewThreads\":{\"nodes\":[{\"id\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"isResolved\":true,\"isOutdated\":false,\"path\":\"crates/but/src/command/legacy/push.rs\",\"line\":258,\"comments\":{\"nodes\":[{\"body\":\"`stacked_on` detection compares `branch_detail.base_commit` to the first local commit (or `base_commit`) of another branch. This is not equivalent to comparing against the other branch’s tip, and can misidentify (or miss) the parent branch in the stack. The prior logic compared `other_branch.tip == branch_detail.base_commit`, which matches the comment and typical stacking semantics.\",\"author\":{\"login\":\"copilot-pull-request-reviewer\"}}]}},{\"id\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"isResolved\":true,\"isOutdated\":false,\"path\":\"crates/but/src/command/legacy/forge/review.rs\",\"line\":968,\"comments\":{\"nodes\":[{\"body\":\"`branch_commits()` uses `applied_stack(ctx, stack_id)` even when `stack_id` is `None`. In that case `applied_stack()` returns the first stack in the workspace, so commit lookup becomes incorrect for any branch that’s not in that first stack (common when `stack_id` is unknown/unstable, e.g. single-branch mode). This can lead to empty/incorrect default PR messages and missing commit lists.\",\"author\":{\"login\":\"copilot-pull-request-reviewer\"}}]}},{\"id\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"isResolved\":true,\"isOutdated\":false,\"path\":\"crates/but/src/legacy/workspace.rs\",\"line\":174,\"comments\":{\"nodes\":[{\"body\":\"`StackId::single_branch_id()` is a valid stack identifier (used for single-branch mode when no managed workspace ref is checked out). Filtering it out here can cause stacks to have `id: None`, which then makes several CLI commands silently ignore the only available stack (many call sites check `stack.id.is_some()`).\",\"author\":{\"login\":\"copilot-pull-request-reviewer\"}}]}},{\"id\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"isResolved\":true,\"isOutdated\":true,\"path\":\"crates/but/src/legacy/workspace.rs\",\"line\":null,\"comments\":{\"nodes\":[{\"body\":\"Using a hard-coded SHA-1 null OID (`gix::hash::Kind::Sha1.null()`) is incorrect for repositories using a different object hash (e.g. SHA-256). Prefer deriving a fallback from an existing OID (tip/commit_id) or from the repository’s `object_hash()` to ensure the null OID has the correct hash kind.\",\"author\":{\"login\":\"copilot-pull-request-reviewer\"}}]}},{\"id\":\"[REDACTED:entropy]\",\"isResolved\":true,\"isOutdated\":false,\"path\":\"crates/but/src/command/legacy/push.rs\",\"line\":258,\"comments\":{\"nodes\":[{\"body\":\"`stacked_on` detection should compare another branch’s *tip* to `branch_detail.base_commit`. Using the first commit in `b.commits` can be incorrect if the commit list is empty, truncated, or not ordered with tip-first, which will misreport the stacking relationship in dry-run output.\",\"author\":{\"login\":\"copilot-pull-request-reviewer\"}}]}}]}}}}}","tool_name":"exec_command","tool_kind":"exec","tool_input":null,"exit_code":0,"outcome":"succeeded","source_record":{"timestamp":"2026-06-03T13:40:34.484Z","type":"response_item","payload":{"type":"function_call_output","call_id":"[REDACTED:entropy]"}}}